[3] Re: listing of scientific experts on bse
Date: Thu, 21 Mar 1996 13:12:05 GMT
Via: Bovine Spongiform Encephalopathy <BSE-L@RZ.UNI-KARLSRUHE.DE>
From: J Ralph Blanchfield <jralphb@easynet.co.uk>
Organization: Consultant
On Wed, 20 Mar 1996 19:21:20 -0500, deeskip@ aol.com wrote:
>i am interested in obtaining a list of experts on bse and its relation to cjd
>or gss or other tse. is such a list available? if not, perhaps there is a
>good review article that lists current contacts in this area. I seem to have
>read of some researchers in the NE USA that have actually "identified" or
>isolated the prions responsible for bse. perhaps you can enlighten me. i
>would like to meet with these experts over the next 6 months. any knowledge
>of upcoming mtgs. where many would gather for discussions? thanks in advance
>for any input you can provide. best regards. skip.
>
Hello Skip,
I am not aware of any "list of experts" but I can give you a few
names.
The prion experts in USA that you refer to are at University of
California, San Fransico, and the key figure there is Stanley B
Prusiner, of the Department of Biochemistry and Biophysics.
The leading independent (i.e. non-governmental) experts in the UK are
those who serve on the Spongiform Encephalopathy Advisory Committee
(SEAC).
I can give you names and locations but not detailed addresses.
The chairman is John Pattinson, professor of clinical microbiology and
dean of the medical school and faculty of clinical sciences at
University College Hospital, London. Other members are
Jeffrey Almond, professor of microbiology, University of Reading
Ray Bradley, animal pathologist, and chairman of the EU Scientific
Veterinary Committee (his location is not known by me)[ try the CVL,
New Haw, Weybridge, Surrey, England. MH-J]
John Collinge, professor and head of the prion diseases group, St
May's Hospital, London
Robert Will, professor and consultant neurologist, Western General
Hospital, Edinburgh (he is vice-chaiman of SEAC, and director of the
CGD Surveillance Unit at Edinburgh).
Fred Brown, head of virology research at the Wellcome Foundation
Ingrid Allen, professor of neuropathology, Queens University, Belfast
William Watson, former director of the Central Veterinary Laboratory
(CVL) of the Ministry of Agriculture Fisheries and Food.
Many of the Government experts and researchers are at CVL, (New Haw,
Weybridge, Surrey)
A great deal of BSE-related research in the UK is carried out at the
Institute of Animal Health (one of the research institutes under the
Biotechnology and Biological Sciences Research Council).
One upcoming meeting on BSE of which I am aware is in Dublin on 8
November [contact <R.JOSEPH@nat_food_centre.hq.teagasc.ie>]
Regards
Ralph
J Ralph Blanchfield
Food Science, Food Technology & Food Law Consultant
Chair, IFST Member Relations & Services Committee
Web Editor, Institute of Food Science & Technology
IFST Web address: http://www.easynet.co.uk/ifst/
[- I have known Ray Bradley since he joined us in the Path Dept, CVL, as
the muscle pathologist. He later succeeded Jack Done, as Dept Head. He is
extremely sound. MH-J]
