[5] BSE and prions
Date: Thu, 21 Mar 1996 12:13:07 GMT
Via: Bovine Spongiform Encephalopathy <BSE-L@rz.uni-karlsruhe.de>
From: J Ralph Blanchfield <jralphb@easynet.co.uk>
On 20 March, Michael Budnick wrote:

>I am new to this group. I have been dealing with the BSE issue for many
>years now as technical director for a biotechnology company. I hope you
>won't mind my commentary on a recent message.
>
>>J. Ralph Blanchfield wrote
>
>>A great deal of research during the past two or three years, on every tissue
>>and secretion from confirmed BSE-infected cows, has demonstrated that
>>infectivity is not found in any but the brain, spinal cord and retina.
>
>Yes, but one problem is that there is no way in a slaughterhouse environment
>that these tissues can effectively be segregated from others. There will
>always be some contamination.
>
>>What can be said is that the hypothesis of infected ruminant feed as the
>>major factor seems to have been confirmed by the banning of ruminant feed
>>being followed, after a delay mainly due to the incubation period, by the
>>dramatic successive reductions in the number of new BSE cases in cattle over
>>the past two years.
>>
>I agree that this may be considered evidence of ruminant feed as the major
>factor, but it is not conclusive of the"sheep to cattle" theory for the
>following reason: since ruminant feed before the ban also consisted of
>bovine material, we may only be seeing an end to amplification of the
>epidemic. The source still might have been other than sheep scrapie, and
>merely amplified by the cattle-to-cattle feeding.

Welcome to BSE-L, Michael.

The ruminant feed hypothesis is not limited to sheep remains but includes
recycled cattle remains.
It is almost certainly multi-factorial, and you may well be right that
cattle remains is an important factor. However, the important point is
that the banning of ruminant feed seems to be working, and it is not merely
"an end to amplification of the epidemic", but a dramatic reduction in new
cases (30 percent drop from 1993 to 1994, 40 percent drop from 1994 to 1995,
and 27.5 percent drop in 1996 so far compared with the same period in 1995).

>To the best of my knowledge, to date no one has fed scrapie-infected sheep
>material to cattle and demonstrated resulting BSE disease, which is the
>definitive experiment. On the contrary: sheep scrapie INJECTED directly into
>cow brains (presented at recent BSE conference at NIH) results in a TSE that
>has completely different characteristics from BSE.

Injection may well produce different results from the oral route, and, in
view of the difference between scrapie infective agent and the BSE
infective agent, the results from a single oral passage of scrapie through
cattle would be unlikely to be definitive.

Incidentally, there are some who speculate that the oral route may not have
been the route (or not the only route), and that infected ruminant dust may
have been absorbed through the eye and direct to the brain. I am not aware
of any research to establish whether that was the case.

Regards

Ralph
J Ralph Blanchfield
